<TITLE>Letter: Cal Water bullies citizens, shows its greedy side</TITLE>


<TEXT>
As a member of Lower Oroville Water Rates (LOWR) I have <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">spent</EVENT> the <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="PAST_REF">past year</TIMEX3> studying the private water company, Cal Water, and I have <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">come</EVENT> to the conclusion that they are the epitome of a greedy corporation. 
 
They have <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">operated</EVENT> for about <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DURATION" value="P100Y">100 years</TIMEX3> without a franchise in Oroville. They <EVENT eid="e4" class="STATE">have</EVENT> no water of their own, so they have to <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">buy</EVENT> it from PG amp;E. They <EVENT eid="e6" class="STATE">charge</EVENT> rates two to four times higher than the other two companies that serve Oroville. They siphon out about $5 million <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DURATION" value="P1Y">a year</TIMEX3> from our city and <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">send</EVENT> it to their home office in San Jose to lavish it on their CEO, executives and stockholders. They <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">neglect</EVENT> their infrastructure and then <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">raise</EVENT> rates when it <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">comes</EVENT> time to finally <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> some upgrades or repairs. 
 
They are <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">trapped</EVENT> between two publicly owned companies, Thermalito Water  amp; Sewer and South Feather Water and Power, so they cannot <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">increase</EVENT> their customers, which means the only way they can <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">raise</EVENT> more revenue is to continually <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">raise</EVENT> their rates. 
 
So, as residents let their trees <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">die</EVENT> and give up on <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">growing</EVENT> gardens because of Cal Water’s onerous rates, and businesses are <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">forced</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">compete</EVENT> with other businesses, sometimes just across the street from them, while <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">paying</EVENT> much higher water rates, Cal Water complains, bullies and threatens because the city <EVENT eid="e21" class="I_STATE">wants</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e22" class="STATE">have</EVENT> a regional water study <EVENT eid="e23" class="I_STATE">done</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e24" class="PERCEPTION">see</EVENT> if they can possibly <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">reduce</EVENT> the water rates for their constituents. Despicable! 
 
— William Bynum, Oroville
</TEXT>


